TableData.TableDescription:
Main volumetric efficiency table.
The values in this table represent the efficiency of the engine's ability to fill the cylinders with air. It is used to predict the volume of air entering each cylinder under varying conditions.
The air mass per cylinder can be determined from the VE table using the following formula: g/cyl = VE*MAP/charge temperature Ve is in g*K/kPa, MAP is in kPa, charge temperature is in degrees Kelvin.
Cylinder volume is used to calculate the VE as a percentage. Changing the cylinder volume will change the VE percentages displayed in this table.

NOTE: Remember this table is based on intake temperature, not coolant temperature.

The PCM calculates the charge temperature (in degrees Kelvin) using the following formula 273.15+IAT+((ECT-IAT)*factor) where factor is obtained from this calibration.
At low airflow "factor" is closer to 1 which weights the charge temperature in favour of ECT. At high airflow (>150g/s) "factor" is closer to 0 which weights the charge temperature in favour of IAT.
The theory being that heat (ECT) is transferred from the heads and manifold after the IAT has been measured and prior to the air entering the cylinder.
If factor is 0, then the charge temperature will be IAT, if factor is 1, then the charge temperature will be ECT, other values for factor will blend the charge temperature between IAT and ECT accordingly.
This calibration is controlled by {B0109} "Blend IAT With ECT".

Determines the rate of change of the calculated charge temperature in response to changes in the IAT or the ECT. Values closer to 1 will cause faster changes, values closer to 0 will cause slower changes.

TableData.TableName: H0101 - Vehicle Speed Sensor Pulses per Mile
TableData.TableDescription:
The number of Pulses the Speed Sensor produces per Mile. This value is used to determine the vehicle's actual Speed, and controls the Speedometer Needle in the Instrument Cluster.
Increasing this value (H0101) will reduce the indicated speed of the Speedometer. Decreasing this value (H0101) will increase the indicated speed of the Speedometer.
This value MUST be manually calculated by YOU. Some tuning software have an automated calculator "Wizard".
H0101 is calculated using this formula: H0101 = (H0102 x H0103 x 63360) ÷ (Tire Diameter x Pi)
Where: H0101 = Vehicle Speed Sensor Pulses per Mile H0102 = Vehicle Speed Sensor (VSS) Pulses per Revolution (typically 17 or 40) H0103 = Axle or Differential Gear Ratio (eg. 3.73) Tire Diameter = tire diameter in inches Pi = 3.14159

TableData.TableName: H0102 - Vehicle Speed Sensor Pulses per Revolution
TableData.TableDescription:
The number of pulses the speed sensor produces per single transmission output shaft (TOS) revolution, which is normally* the same as the number of teeth on the vehicle speed sensor's reluctor ring.
For manual vehicles, it is not used and is sometimes set incorrectly. The normal values used for this calibration are 17 and 40. Manual gearboxes are usually 17 and automatic transmissions are usually 40. However, some trucks with manual gearboxes use 40.
For automatic vehicles, it is used by the PCM to determine the transmission shift speeds and will normally be consistent with the equation: H0101=H0102*H0104.
* Corvettes have this value calibrated to "40 divided by actual diff ratio" (regardless of whether they are manual or automatic) since the reluctor ring is located on the rear transaxle - not the transmission output shaft.

This value is used by the torque subsystem to estimate the axle torque.
It is not used by the PCM for calculating either the speedometer or the transmission shift speeds. On many vehicles (especially corvettes) it is set incorrectly, usually to the default value of 2.73 regardless of the actual differential ratio.

It will normally be consistent with the equation: H0101=H0102*H0104.
